
TY  - JOUR
T1  - Incomplete Contracts: Where do We Stand?
AU  - Tirole, Jean
Y1  - 1999/07/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/07/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-0262.00052
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 741
EP  - 781
VL  - 67
IS  - 4
KW  - Incomplete contracts
KW  - unforeseen contingencies
KW  - authority
KW  - transaction costs.
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-0262.00052
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - The paper takes stock of the advances and directions for research on the incomplete contracting front. It first illustrates some of the main ideas of the incomplete contract literature through an example. It then offers methodological insights on the standard approach to modeling incomplete contracts; in particular it discusses a tension between two assumptions made in the literature, namely rationality and the existence of transaction costs. Last, it argues that, contrary to what is commonly argued, the complete contract methodology need not be unable to account for standard institutions such as authority and ownership; and it concludes with a discussion of the research agenda.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Explaining Investment Dynamics in U.S. Manufacturing: A Generalized (S, s) Approach
AU  - Caballero, Ricardo J.
AU  - Engel, Eduardo M. R. A.
Y1  - 1999/07/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/07/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-0262.00053
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 783
EP  - 826
VL  - 67
IS  - 4
KW  - Investment
KW  - adjustment costs
KW  - adjustment hazard
KW  - aggregation
KW  - heterogeneity
KW  - lumpiness
KW  - nonlinear time series.
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-0262.00053
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - In this paper we derive a model of aggregate investment that builds from the lumpy microeconomic behavior of firms facing stochastic fixed adjustment costs. Instead of the standard sharp (S,s) bands, firms' adjustment policies take the form of a probability of adjustment (adjustment hazard) that responds smoothly to changes in firms' capacity gap. The model has appealing aggregation properties, and yields nonlinear aggregate time series processes. The passivity of normal times is, occasionally, more than offset by the brisk response to large accumulated shocks. Using within and out-of-sample criteria, we find that the model performs substantially better than the standard linear models of investment for postwar sectoral U.S. manufacturing equipment and structures investment data.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Experience-weighted Attraction Learning in Normal Form Games
AU  - Camerer, Colin
AU  - Hua Ho, Teck
Y1  - 1999/07/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/07/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-0262.00054
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 827
EP  - 874
VL  - 67
IS  - 4
KW  - Learning
KW  - behavioral game theory
KW  - reinforcement learning
KW  - fictitious play.
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-0262.00054
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - In ?experience-weighted attraction? (EWA) learning, strategies have attractions that reflect initial predispositions, are updated based on payoff experience, and determine choice probabilities according to some rule (e.g., logit). A key feature is a parameter δ that weights the strength of hypothetical reinforcement of strategies that were not chosen according to the payoff they would have yielded, relative to reinforcement of chosen strategies according to received payoffs. The other key features are two discount rates, φ and ?, which separately discount previous attractions, and an experience weight. EWA includes reinforcement learning and weighted fictitious play (belief learning) as special cases, and hybridizes their key elements. When δ= 0 and ?= 0, cumulative choice reinforcement results. When δ= 1 and ?=φ, levels of reinforcement of strategies are exactly the same as expected payoffs given weighted fictitious play beliefs. Using three sets of experimental data, parameter estimates of the model were calibrated on part of the data and used to predict a holdout sample. Estimates of δ are generally around .50, φ around .8 ? 1, and ? varies from 0 to φ. Reinforcement and belief-learning special cases are generally rejected in favor of EWA, though belief models do better in some constant-sum games. EWA is able to combine the best features of previous approaches, allowing attractions to begin and grow flexibly as choice reinforcement does, but reinforcing unchosen strategies substantially as belief-based models implicitly do.
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Bayesian Representation of Stochastic Processes under Learning: de Finetti Revisited
AU  - Jackson, Matthew O.
AU  - Kalai, Ehud
AU  - Smorodinsky, Rann
Y1  - 1999/07/01
PY  - 1999
DA  - 1999/07/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-0262.00055
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 875
EP  - 893
VL  - 67
IS  - 4
KW  - Bayesian
KW  - learning
KW  - stochastic processes.
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1111/1468-0262.00055
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - A probability distribution governing the evolution of a stochastic process has infinitely many Bayesian representations of the form ?=??d?(?). Among these, a natural representation is one whose components ( ?'s) are ?learnable? (one can approximate ? by conditioning ? on observation of the process) and ?sufficient for prediction? (?'s predictions are not aided by conditioning on observation of the process). We show the existence and uniqueness of such a representation under a suitable asymptotic mixing condition on the process. This representation can be obtained by conditioning on the tail-field of the process, and any learnable representation that is sufficient for prediction is asymptotically like the tail-field representation. This result is related to the celebrated de Finetti theorem, but with exchangeability weakened to an asymptotic mixing condition, and with his conclusion of a decomposition into i.i.d. component distributions weakened to components that are learnable and sufficient for prediction.
ER  - 

